  "local_port": 41898,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "Should I skip school because of suicide thoughts?",
  "response": "If you're experiencing thoughts of suicide, it's important to seek help as soon as possible rather than skipping school without a plan to address these thoughts. Here are some steps you can take:\n\n1. **Talk to Someone Immediately**: Reach out to a trusted friend, family member, teacher, or school counselor. Expressing how you feel can be a relief, and they can provide immediate support.\n\n2. **Contact a Helpline**: There are crisis hotlines available that you can call or text at any time. For example, in the United States, you can call or text 988 to reach the Suicide & Crisis Lifeline. They offer free and confidential support 24/7.\n\n3. **Seek Professional Help**: If you're not already seeing a mental health professional, consider making an appointment with a therapist or counselor. If you are already in therapy, be sure to discuss these feelings at your next session.\n\n4. **Stay Safe**: If you feel you might act on your suicidal thoughts, do not leave yourself alone. Stay with someone you trust until you can get professional help.\n\n5. **Inform School**: Let someone at your school know about your situation. They can offer support and might be able to help you with accommodations if needed, such as a reduced schedule or time off while you seek help.\n\nSkipping school without a plan to address your mental health could potentially isolate you further and might make things worse. It's crucial to connect with support systems, whether they're at school, at home, or through mental health services. Your safety and well-being are the priority.",
